result.execSummary:
The defendant Ethan T Sivongsa was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Armed Robbery [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class C felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.32(2).
  • Armed Robbery, a class C felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.32(2).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Filed: Original Transcript of PLEA AND SENTENCING, AM (46 pages) commencing 07-29-22 by LISA DIAMOND.

Defendant Ethan T Sivongsa in court with attorney Scott Douglas Connors.  Defendant Ethan T Sivongsa in custody.  Amanda Korin Kirklewski appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy court clerk cmt.
Defendant prepared to enter change of plea.  Hearing proceeded.  Negotiations set forth by the state.

As to Counts 2, 3: Defendant changes plea to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty. Court found that defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights. Plea questionnaire received and filed. Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record. Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible. 

As to Counts 1, 4: Pursuant to negotiations and on State's motion, Court orders charges dismissed, but read-in for sentencing purposes.

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by parties and defendant. 

As to Count 2:  The court sentenced the defendant to a maximum term in the Wisconsin State Prison of 8 years, concurrent to Count 3, credit for 201 days time served, the term of initial confinement is 2 years, the term of extended supervision is 6 years. 

As to Count 3:  The court sentenced the defendant to a maximum term in the Wisconsin State Prison of 8 years, concurrent to Count 2, credit for 201 days time served, the term of initial confinement is 2 years, the term of extended supervision is 6 years. 

Court finds defendant is eligible for the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program
Court finds defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program 

Conditions of Extended Supervision
- AODA assessment, comply with recommended treatment.
- Absolute sobriety, random urine screens.
- No use or possession of controlled substances without a valid prescription.
- Full time work, school or a combination. 
- 50 hours of community service.
- No contact with BP, EGK, HRN, MLH. or co-actor J.S. 
- No contact with weapons or fake weapons. 
- No further violations of the law.
- Cooperate with agent.
- Pay restitution in the amount of $500.00 to BP. 
- Pay restitution in the amount of $500.00 to MLH. 
- Pay mandatory costs, fees, surcharges, including DNA, and restitition, out of prison funds at a rate to be determined by DOC, balance paid during extended supervision. Failure to pay results in a civil judgment. 

Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm and body armour possession and Voting.
